{"body":"## Problem\n\nThere is no documentation warning users that this MCP server **must be the sole consumer** of its configured Telegram bot token. If another component (e.g., `scitex-orochi`'s Telegram bridge) also polls the same bot token, the Telegram Bot API returns **HTTP 409 Conflict** errors, causing one or both consumers to miss messages.\n\n## Background\n\nThe Telegram Bot API enforces a single active `getUpdates` long-polling connection per bot token. When two processes compete for updates on the same token:\n\n- One receives a 409 error and is disconnected\n- Messages may be acknowledged by one consumer but needed by the other\n- Reconnection attempts create a flapping loop\n\n## Proposal\n\nAdd clear documentation covering:\n\n1. **Exclusivity requirement** — this server must be the only process calling `getUpdates` on the configured bot token.\n2. **Common conflict scenario** — if `scitex-orochi`'s Telegram bridge is enabled with the same token, 409 errors will occur.\n3. **Resolution options**:\n   - Disable orochi's Telegram bridge when using this MCP server\n   - Use a separate bot token for each component\n   - Route all Telegram traffic through a single polling component\n\n### Suggested locations\n\n- `README.md` — add a \"Requirements\" or \"Important Notes\" section\n- Startup log — emit a warning if 409 errors are detected\n\n## Related\n\n- ywatanabe1989/scitex-orochi — issue tracking bot token ownership clarification","title":"docs: document Telegram bot token exclusivity requirement"}

